Let's analyze the functions A, B, and C.

A(x) is a recursive function that calculates the x-th Fibonacci number. The Fibonacci sequence grows exponentially. So A(123456789) will be a very large number.

B(x) is a recursive function that essentially doubles the value of B(x/2) until x becomes less than or equal to 1.  Since B(1) = 1, B(x) can be thought of as 2 raised to the power of the number of times x can be divided by 2 before it becomes less than or equal to 1. The number of times a number can be divided by 2 before it becomes less than or equal to 1 is proportional to log base 2 of the number. Thus B(x) grows logarithmically.

C(x) calculates 1 + C(x - 10). If x < 0, C(x) = 0.  Therefore C(x) returns the number of times we can subtract 10 from x before it becomes negative, plus 1. Thus C(x) = 1 + floor(x/10) if x >= 0 and 0 otherwise.  So C(123456789) will be 1 + 12345678. C(x) grows linearly.

Therefore, A(x) will be the largest, followed by B(x) and C(x).
A(x) is exponential (Fibonacci).
B(x) is logarithmic (power of 2).
C(x) is linear.

We have a = A(123456789), b = B(123456789), and c = C(123456789). Since A is Fibonacci, B is logarithmic, and C is linear, we have c < b < a.

